{
  "doc_id": "30869",
  "text": "Neural-circuit modeling has proven itself as a fast and versatile method to study and understand the operation of specific neural circuits. Consequently, a large number of models with increasing levels of complexity and degree of detail are being developed [CITATION_1] ), yet neural modeling usually requires some assumptions to be made. These assumptions are usually made based on the operation of the modeled circuits. This is particularly true in developing functional models that must solve a task or mimic an expected behavior. Some of these assumptions determine the efficiency and flexibility of the input-output mapping of a supervised-learning circuit [CITATION_2] . A function for evaluating the input representation must assess this representation according to the model inputoutput mapping capabilities. Our evaluation function is tailored according to those models of supervised-learning circuits that assume that (i) synaptic weights converge to an optimal solution (as suggested in [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , (ii) the effect of simultaneous input activity on several readoutneuron synapses is additive, and (iii) the input state is codified through excitatory activity.",
